'''Dragendorff's reagent''' is a color [[reagent]] to detect [[alkaloid]]s in a test sample. Alkaloids, if present in the solution of sample, will react with Dragendorff's reagent and produce an orange or orange red [[precipitate]].<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Nayeem AA, Khatun A, Rahman MS, Rahman M | title = Evaluation of phytochemical and pharmacological properties of Mikania cordata (Asteraceae) leaves | journal = Journal of Pharmacognosy and Phytotherapy | date = 2011 | volume = 3 | issue = 8 | pages = 118–123}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author = Ghani A. | title = Medicinal Plants of Bangladesh | edition = 1st | publisher = The Asiatic Society of Bangladesh | location = Dhaka, Bangladesh | date = 1998 | page = 505}}</ref> This reagent was invented by the German pharmacologist, Johann Georg Dragendorff (1836&ndash;1898) at the [[University of Dorpat]].
==Composition== Dragendroff's reagent is a solution of potassium bismuth iodide prepared from basic [[bismuth nitrate]] (Bi(NO<sub>3</sub>)<sub>3</sub>), [[tartaric acid]], and [[potassium iodide]] (KI).<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Khatun A, Rahman M, Jahan S | title = Preliminary phytochemical and pharmacological screening of Murraya exotica Linn. leaves extract | journal = Oriental Pharmacy and Experimental Medicine | date = 2014 | volume = 14 | issue = 3 | pages = 223–229 | doi = 10.1007/s13596-014-0150-x}}</ref>
