ure prompts retraction of Oncogene paper by Roman-Gomez | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2013/02/08/lifted-figure-prompts-retraction-of-oncogene-paper-by-roman-gomez/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2013-02-08|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = JCO expresses concern over images from Spanish group that had aroused earlier concern |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2012/04/05/jco-expresses-concern-over-western-blots-from-spanish-group-that-had-aroused-earlier-concern/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2012-04-05|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> Román-Gómez has had six of his publications retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Sixth Retraction for Leukemia Researcher | first = Andrew S. | last = Wiecek | name-list-format = vanc | url = https://www.biotechniques.com/news/340546|publisher=BioTechniques | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180330075950/https://www.biotechniques.com/news/340546 | archive-date = 30 March 2018 |date=2013-03-05|access-date=2018-03-29}}</ref> * [[Steven S. Rosenfeld]] (US), a former Harvard undergraduate, forged [[letters of recommendation]] for himself in the name of David Dressler, whose laboratory he used. His research on [[transfer factor]], on which two articles were published in the ''[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]]'', could not be successfully replicated by other scientists. * Robert Ryan (UK), formerly of the [[University of Dundee]], was found by a University committee in 2016 to have committed research misconduct in his work on molecular bacteriology.<ref>{{cite web | title = University of Dundee scientist resigns after research misconduct | url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/education/university-of-dundee-scientist-resigns-after-research-misconduct-1-4334327 | work = The Scotsman | publisher=Johnston Publishing Ltd.|date=2017-01-08|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> Four of Ryan's publications have been retracted.<ref>{{cite web | title = Caught Our Notice: Former rising star loses fourth paper | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2018/03/21/caught-our-notice-former-rising-star-loses-fourth-paper/ |publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-03-21|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> * Fazlul Sarkar (US), a pathologist formerly at [[Wayne State University]], was in 2015 found by a University committee to have "engaged in and permitted (and tacitly encouraged) intentional and knowing fabrication, falsification, and/or plagiarism of data, and its publication in journals, and its use to support his federal grant applications."<ref>{{cite web | title = Investigation Finds Pathologist Guilty of Systemic Misconduct | url = https://www.the-scientist.com/?articles.view/articleNo/47297/title/Investigation-Finds-Pathologist-Guilty-of-Systemic-Misconduct/|publisher=The Scientist|date=2016-10-09|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> Sarkar, who in 2016 lost a defamation lawsuit he brought against anonymous critics of his work,<ref>{{cite web | title = PubPeer wins appeal of court ruling to unmask commenters | url = https://retractionwatch.com/2016/12/07/pubpeer-wins-appeal-court-ruling-unmask-commenters/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-12-07|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> has had 33 of his publications retracted, and at least a dozen others corrected.<ref>{{cite web | title = Researcher who once tried to sue critics has another dozen papers retracted | url =https://retractionwatch.com/2018/09/17/researcher-who-once-tried-to-sue-critics-has-another-dozen-papers-retracted/#more-71450|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2018-09-17|access-date=2018-09-18}}</ref> * Yoshihiro Sato (Japan), a researcher in [[osteoporosis]] at Mitate Hospital in [[Tagawa, Fukuoka|Tagawa]], published more than 200 papers involving 33 clinical trials, of which 30 trials have been retracted (as of August 2018) either by Sato or by the journals.<ref>http://science.sciencemag.org/content/361/6403/636</ref> * Eric J. Smart (US), a former nutrition researcher, associate professor, vice-chairman of the Department of Pe