== Chemistry ==
* Claudio Airoldi (Brazil), former professor at the [[University of Campinas]], and Denis de Jesus Lima Guerra (Brazil), former professor at the [[Federal University of Mato Grosso]], have had 13 of their papers retracted<ref>{{cite web | title = Researcher in Brazil earns 12th retraction for recycling text and figures |url=https://retractionwatch.com/2016/08/16/researcher-in-brazil-earns-12th-retraction-for-recycling-text-and-figures/|publisher=Retraction Watch|date=2016-08-16|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> in what was reported as the biggest case of scientific fraud in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|title=Autor da maior fraude científica do Brasil é exonerado da UFMT|url=http://www.olhardireto.com.br/noticias/exibir.asp?id=358847}}</ref> * [[Henk Buck]] (Netherlands), former professor of Physical Organic Chemistry and Organic Chemistry at the [[Eindhoven University of Technology]], was directly involved in The Buck-Goudsmit controversy, in which a potential method to inhibit [[HIV-1]] replication was ultimately shown to be based on flawed research.<ref name="Science Retraction">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moody HM, Quaedflieg PJ, Koole LH, van Genderen MH, Buck HM, Smit L, Jurriaans S, Geelen JL, Goudsmit J | title = Inhibition of HIV-1 infectivity by phosphate-methylated DNA: retraction | journal = Science | volume = 250 | issue = 4977 | pages = 125–26 | date = October 1990 | pmid = 2218505 | doi = 10.1126/science.2218505 }}</ref><ref name="pmid2218505">{{cite journal | vauthors = Moody HM, Quaedflieg PJ, Koole LH, van Genderen MH, Buck HM, Smit L, Jurriaans S, Geelen JL, Goudsmit J | title = Inhibition of HIV-1 infectivity by phosphate-methylated DNA: retraction | journal = Science | volume = 250 | issue = 4977 | pages = 125–6 | date = October 1990 | pmid = 2218505 | doi = | url = http://science.sciencemag.org/content/sci/250/4977/125.full.pdf }}</ref> * Juan Carlos Mejuto (Spain) and Gonzalo Astray Dopazo (Spain) of the [[University of Vigo]] had two papers retracted in 2011 because "significant portions" of the papers duplicated previously published work.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alicia |last=Rivera |title=Ciencia china 'duplicada' en Galicia |url=http://www.elpais.com/articulo/sociedad/Ciencia/china/duplicada/Galicia/elpepisoc/20110520elpepisoc_8/Tes | publisher=El País | date=May 20, 2011 }}{{cite news |first=Paul |last=Ingendaay |title=War die Guttenberg-Affäre denn zu gar nichts gut?|url=http://www.faz.net/IN/INtemplates/faznet/default.asp?tpl=common/zwischenseite.asp&dx1={B43A6DE1-AB1B-0749-EF51-A4D52091788B}|publisher= Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung |date=June 15, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=Addition/Correction: Prediction of Refractive Index of Polymers Using Artificial Neural Networks |volume=56 |page=688 |date=2010-02-09 |journal= Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data |doi=10.1021/je200071p |issue=3|last1=Astray |first1=G |last2=Cid |first2=A |last3=Moldes |first3=O |last4=Ferreiro-Lage |first4=J. A |last5=GáLvez |first5=J. F |last6=Mejuto |first6=J. C }}{{Cite journal |title=Addition/Correction: Prediction of Prop-2-enoate Polymer and Styrene Polymer Glass Transition Using Artificial Neural Networks |volume=56 |page=689 |date=2010-02-09 |journal= Journal of Chemical & Engineering Data |doi=10.1021/je200072e |issue=3|last1=Astray |first1=G |last2=Cid |first2=A |last3=Ferreiro-Lage |first3=J. A |last4=GáLvez |first4=J. F |last5=Mejuto |first5=J. C |last6=Nieto-Faza |first6=O }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Something rotten in the state of Spain, say whistleblowers|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/something-rotten-in-the-state-of-spain-say-whistleblowers/420782.article|publisher=Times Higher Education|date=2018-08-09|access-date=2018-04-16}}</ref> * [[Leo Paquette#Scientific misconduct|Leo Paquette]] (US), an Ohio State University professor, plagiarized sections from an unfunded NIH grant application for use in his own NIH grant application.<ref name="NIH">{{Citation | title = Final Findings of Scientific Misconduct | author = Office of Research Integrity | date = June 25, 1993 | publisher= DHHS | periodical = Nih Guide | volume = 22 | issue = 23 | url = https://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/notice-files/not93-177.html | access-date = October 3, 2016 }}</ref> He also plagiarized a NSF proposal for use in one of his scientific publications.<ref name="C&EN-Misconduct">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zurer P | title = NSF, Paquette Settle Misconduct Case | journal = Chemical & Engineering News |volume = 76 | issue = 10 | pages = 25–26 | date = March 9, 1998 | doi= 10.1021/cen-v076n010.p025 }}</ref><ref name="OSU">{{Citation | title = Scientific Misconduct Charge Ruled Valid | last = Gerstner | first = Ruth | date = August 9, 1993 | publisher= Ohio State University | url = https://news.osu.edu/news/1993/08/09/93-08-09_Scientific_Misconduct_Charge_Ruled_Valid/ | access-date = October 3, 2016 }}</ref> * H. Zhong, T. Liu, and their colleagues (China) at [[Jinggangshan University]] have retracted at least 70 papers published in [[Acta Crystallographica]]<ref name="pmid21579903">{{cite journal | vauthors = Zhong H, Duan SH, Hong YP, Li ML, Liu YQ, Luo CJ, Luo QY, Xiao SZ, Xie HL, Xu YP, Yang XM, Zeng XR, Zhong QY | title = Retraction of articles by H. Zhong et al | journal = Acta Crystallographica Section E | volume = 66 | issue = Pt 1 | pages = e11–2 | date = December 2009 | pmid = 21579903 | pmc = 2980006 | doi = 10.1107/S1600536809049964 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Retraction of articles by T. Liu et al. | url = https://journals.iucr.org/e/issues/2010/01/00/me0405/index.html|publisher=International Union of Crystallography|date=2010-01-01|access-date=2018-04-12}}</ref> following analyses that revealed the organic structures claimed in these papers to be impossible or implausible; the supporting data appeared to have been taken from valid structures that had then been altered by substituting atoms.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Harrison WT, Simpson J, Weil M | title = Editorial | journal = Acta Crystallographica Section E | volume = 66 | issue = Pt 1 | pages = e1–2 | date = December 2009 | pmid = 21579902 | pmc = 2980207 | doi = 10.1107/S1600536809051757 | url = http://journals.iucr.org/e/issues/2010/01/00/me0406/ }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/8448731.stm |title=Lancet urges China to tackle scientific fraud |author=Doreen Walton |publisher=BBC |date=8 January 2010}}</ref> * Guido Zadel (Germany), published an article with the title "Enantioselective Reactions in a Static Magnetic Field" in 1994.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zadel |first1=Guido |last2=Eisenbraun |first2=Catia |last3=Wolff |first3=Gerd-Joachim |last4=Breitmaier |first4=Eberhard |title=Enantioselective Reactions in a Static Magnetic Field |journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition in English |date=3 March 1994 |volume=33 |issue=4 |pages=454–456 |doi=10.1002/anie.199404541}}</ref> His experiments had been manipulated, which led to the retraction of the respective paper and the final loss of his doctoral degree in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bonner Chemiker verliert Doktortitel |url=https://idw-online.de/en/news76031 |website=idw-online.de |language=de}}</ref> The German version of the article is still accessible at Angew. Chem. in 2018 for $59 without any obvious retraction note.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Zadel |first1=Guido |last2=Eisenbraun |first2=Catja |last3=Wolff |first3=Gerd-Joachim |last4=Breitmaier |first4=Eberhard |title=Enantioselektive Reaktionen im statischen Magnetfeld |journal=Angewandte Chemie |date=18 February 1994 |volume=106 |issue=4 |pages=460–463 |doi=10.1002/ange.19941060417}}</ref>
